com:
I've recently read some old interviews with the writer and illustrator of Asterix. At some point they mentioned that when they first created Asterix the market researchers were pointing out that cartoon/comics protagonists have to be young, handsome and talk about modern issues in order to be relatable to the young audience.

Who the fuck make these "market researches"? Do they actually make any research or they make up shit from their heads? Why are these "researchers" still obsessed with the idea that a movie/series protagonist has to be "relatable" in order to sell? Most popular media from the long past till now have anything but "relatable" protagonist: from ugly sailors till cartoonish anthropomorphic sponges.

Besides the young audience (especially little kids) don't actually give a shit about "representation". They want to see kickass/funny/entertaining media. Nobody gives a shit about human characters in Trasformers media. Nobody gives a shit about little kids side characters at shows with older/adult protagonists. On the contrary most kids find these kind of "relatable" characters pointless and annoying and many of them have been quickly removed and never been used again.

com:
The days grow colder, the nights grow longer. That means /co/ Christmas cheer is coming to town. Grab some cocoa, turn on the Christmas music, get comfy, and hang out with some /co/mrades as we share stories and get into the holiday spirit.

As previous years, share your Amazon wishlist and some random Anon may purchase a holiday gift for you. Be sure to gift another Anon in return so we can spread the cheer far and wide.

Please check the Pastebin to learn how to get your wishlist code, add a shipping address, the benefits of using AmazonSmile, and all other information.

Last year we had 132 gifted anons, some more than once.

Ungifted lists: pastebin.com/SmVHgMRE
All lists: pastebin.com/ZCXuvfE5

To get your wishlist code, open your wishlist on Amazon, then copy the 11 digit number from the link. It will look like this: amazon.com/hz/wishlist/ls/###########
We just need the ###########

Missing Address: When viewing your list, click the "…" in the upper right hand corner. From there click "Manage List" which will give you a few options including “Shipping Address”. While you’re here please check “Third party shipping agreement”. That will allow anons to buy you stuff that isn’t sold by amazon.

name: Anonymous
com:
Somewhere in the infinite Multiverse, there exists a version of the Marvel Universe where, instead of a Peter Parker who was bitten by a radioactive spider, there exists a Petra Parker who was stung by a radioactive honey bee, becoming the heroine: The Heroic Honey-Bee!

here's a rundown of the rules of this universe:
>Only Peter Parker and his costumed friends and enemies (be them hero or villain) are changed, except for Dr. Connors, because it's funny
>Non-costumed folks (i.e. JJJ, Aunt May and Uncle Ben, MJ, Gwen Stacy, Harry, etc.) are not swapped, though their characters may be affected
>The outside Marvel Universe (Avengers, F4, X-men, Daredevil and Hell's Kitchen group) are unchanged
>Swaps are more than just gender, but also in concept (i.e. Instead of a proficient illusionist, we have an incompetent witch. Instead of a villain themed to an aquatic creature with multiple limbs, we have a villain themed to a land animal with multiple legs, etc.)

Wiki: https://cor63au.fandom.com/wiki/The_Heroic_Honey-Bee

name: Anonymous
com:
>Human leads are Noah (Anthony Ramos), an ex-military electronics expert struggling to provide for his mother and sick kid brother, and Elena (Dominique Fishback), an aspiring historian who works as a secretary in the museum and is overlooked for being a young woman.

>Autobots are Optimus Prime, Bumblebee, Arcee, Mirage, Wheeljack and Stratosphere. They are living among humans in secret and protecting them from the Decepticons. Optimus fights a nameless Decepticon bus in the opening scene.

>Bumblebee is sidelined in favor of Mirage, who is presented as the cool young rebel who bonds with the human protagonist Noah. Arcee is Optimus’ second-in-command, Wheeljack is the nerdy comic relief, and Stratosphere is literally there for one scene to transport the heroes to Peru.

>Terrorcons are Scourge, Nightbird, Battletrap and a couple of jobbers. They are factionless Transformers who now serve Unicron and need the Transwarp keys under the Maximals’ protection to bring him to Earth.

>Maximals are Optimus Primal, Airazor, Cheetor and Rhinox. Primal is the leader who mentors Optimus about trusting humans for a bit. Airazor is the wise plot exposition character. Cheetor and Rhinox are just there. Rhinox only has one gag line.

>No Predacons other than an army of Scorponoks in the third act.

>The big twist is that the Michael Bay movies are canon. The Autobots defeated Unicron in that timeline, so he recruited the Terrorcons to use the Transwarp keys to travel back in time and ensure his victory, but the Maximals stole the keys and ended up to pre-historic times, and have been hiding on Earth ever since.

>Like in J.J. Abrams’ Star Trek reboot, time travel caused a new timeline to be created where events were not the same as they were in the Bayverse, and that’s the Bumblebee/Rise of the Beasts timeline which the new movies will follow until they inevitably attempt a crossover with the Bayverse.

name: Shang-Xu biggest fan
com:
This thread is a /co/ collaborative space where anons pitch concepts, write episodes, and draw production art for the greatest toy commercial animated series from the 80s that never was (but everyone still remembers) : Stargaze and the Sentinels of Starlight!

>The story thus far
Star-ro, Prince of the cracked planet Astray, wields the Royal Blaster (a relic of immeasurable power containing the last shard of the Lightstar) as the Hero Stargaze!
Alongside him in this noble quest to bring prosperity to the galaxy, and defeat those who spread evil, are a wide cast of friends and comrades, the Sentinels of Starlight.

Chief among them are:
Conshock: the cloven hoofed psychic pugilist on a quest to save a loved one
Usra-La: The beautiful and ferocious Bar-Barean shaman warrior, seeking to prove herself and her natural ways.
Rock-it: the fearsome yet kind-hearted guardian of the Geosphere
Lanstar: The tech savvy friend of Star-ro
Comet: The half Baastanian half sister of Star-ro, always causing mischief and befriending monsters!

Along with the cerebral Trancia, illustrious Pum-mel, tenacious Krogdar, shifty Shang-Xu, packrat scrapper Tonns, warrior of the shadows Jet-Hawk, honorable Hammer Hex, the incredible Robo-Puppy, and many more!

Champion of justice Stargaze and his faithful sentinels combat many agents of evil, like Astrayan traitor Warmaster, the voracious Hogmaw and Jawbreaker, the rogue robotic AI Wireshark, the seductive insect queen Cicadre and her manipulative assassin Scorpionic, the mysterious and vicious technomancer Sigil, and the master of evil himself: The Nefarious Nebullious!
Creature of terror, the void made form with the dastardly ability to SUMMON SEVERAL HUNDRED SMOKE SNAKES! Enemy of all who look for peace in the lightstar galaxy. He seeks the Royal Blaster and should he get it cosmos will never know peace!

>What is this thread?
Every Wins'day at Win-O'-Clock we gather here and post links to the latest scans and rips of comic books.
Most links we uploaded ourselves, others we are sharing from elsewhere.
Some comics we've even purchased ourselves (but most we didn't).
If you'd like to help out, just ask and we would be delighted to tell you how.
Otherwise, be patient, be polite, and understand the simple concept behind these words: Not posted means not available yet.

>Where can I find old Win-O'-Threads?
http://desuarchive.org/co/search/subject/Official%20Win-O'-Thread/
http://boards.fireden.net/co/search/subject/Official%20Win-O'-Thread/
(Note: This finds the OP for old threads. If you want to search for comics in the archive, clear the subject field!)

>Where can I find downloads for other comics?
Warez forums/blogs, DDL-indexing search engines (like FilesLoop), torrent trackers (like 1337x) and other P2P networks (like DC++).
If a link has been posted on 4chan, you can search for it in the Desu archive (add "http*" to searches to return only posts with links).
If all else fails, just >buy it.

>Where can I buy comics?
http://www.amazon.com/
On the various publishers' webstores, and at your local comics shop.

>Where can I find an LCS?
http://www.comicshoplocator.com/

>Where can I find out when new comics are released?
http://www.comiclist.com/index.php
http://www.previewsworld.com

>How do I download from websites that only give me .exe files?
Untick the checkbox under the download button.

>How can I find this thread every week?
If you are using the inline extension go to http://4chan.org/co/official or use the option under "Filters & Post Hiding".
If you have 4chanX go to Settings > Filter > Subject and add the following line:
/Official Win-O'-Thread/;highlight

>And last but not least
I do this in hopes of mango

My understanding is that Mickey will likely be in a Sherlock Holmes-esque situation where yes you can use steamboat willie Mickey, but since you can't use later versions all disney's lawyers would need to do is point to some trait from a later appearance and claim copyright violation based on that and with the amount of money and lawyers they have it'll probably work. I doubt many people are going to do much with Micky just because of how much of a legal minefield it'll likely be.', 'time': 1670928421, 'resto': 134504182}, {'no': 134509902, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)06:02:31', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>134504182
Any long running franchise is difficult to deal with if only part of it is public domain.
Until 2014 ( see https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/sherlock-holmes-now-officially-copyright-and-open-business-180951794/) it wasn't established that characters from partially public domain franchises fell into the public domain at all. Aspects of a character that were introduced in non-PD material are also still under copyright under the current interpretation of the law. So Mickey Mouse will enter public domain in 2024, but you'll still be at risk of gettin sued by Disney if you use any elements that aren't from Steamboat Willie.', 'time': 1670929351, 'resto': 134504182}, {'no': 134509988, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)06:16:42', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>134509954

I feel like it’s impossible to do a conversion story episode without coming off as preachy and a little offensive. By converting to anything or believing in anything, you are saying “this belief system is true. Others are false, incomplete, or in some way inferior.” Now, peoples real lives aren’t tv shows. It’s good for people to have some convictions, and irl people can tell their story and be tactful about their beliefs. com:
>Nooooo you can't just triage a movie if you know it's gonna flop! It's not bad, it's only mediocre! A mediocre movie still deserves a $200+ million marketing campaign, it probabaly would have made $100 million back which is better than nothing!

First of all, we don't know how much money Disney spent on Strange World's marketing so I am not going to immediately buy into the notion that it was hung out to dry by the studio. Having said that, the movie was going to be a hard sell no matter how much money they threw at it. The character designs are ugly, the story is a mess just like Lightyear, and the Strange World itself is simply not appealing. The thing that was supposed to save this movie was the LGBT appeal, and clearly the LGBT either did not show up to watch it or Disney greatly overestimated how many of them there are. However much Disney spent marketing the movie, it was not going to be commercially viable. The one thing it has going for it appeals to a very small niche audience, and there's nothing about it to appeal to the general audience.

Personally, I'd consider anything which was either publicly displayed or promoted, finished or otherwise, but is not available to the public in some form, is lost. Something which was only known to the creators, but later discussed after the fact as something which they abandoned is certainly debatable.', 'time': 1670911381, 'resto': 134503003}, {'no': 134509382, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)04:34:47', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>134508030

Not if the dub is just on some tapes at some network. Its "accessible" (in ways not available to normal people) , not lost, until proven otherwise.', 'time': 1670924087, 'resto': 134503003}, {'no': 134509388, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)04:36:14', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>134503051
if a good amount of material was shot/produced, then it already counts desu', 'time': 1670924174, 'resto': 134503003}, {'no': 134509457, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)04:51:51', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>134503003
There's different sections on lost media wikis/forums. Generally it goes down the whole scale, but what would be considered "Lost" is something which WAS made, but isn't archived in any accessible way/available to purchase for the general public. This can scale from media released scarcely and never recorded (that we know of), media which literally doesn't exist anymore (because the only surviving copies were destroyed), and media which was created but never released (I.E. show finale which was made but never released).
Scale goes something like this, because a lot of lost media, by definition, goes off someone's memory of events:
>Literally never created
Generally, this type of "lost media" is media which people misremember as other things, which when located answer the question of "that other thing isn't real, i remembered it wrong, this is what i was talking about." Think the Evil Farming Game mystery which Justin Whang went over a while back. Sometimes this refers to show concepts never even made, whether confirmed by a piece of media's creators or not (often distinguished between confirmed never existed and believed never existed)
>Made, but not released
Stuff which shows up in deleted scenes/blooper reels or is later released by their original creators. Either not initially released on account of copyright/contract fuckery, or cancellation of a given property. Arguably not lost, just unreleased, since nobody would've seen it besides its creators, but if destroyed, it would inarguably be lost media, so generally the fact that you can't see it generally leads to it being considered as such.
>Existed, publicly aired, now lost.
What most people mean by lost media. Typically defined by a lack of a definitive high quality rip online, often as a result of no real home video release (due to something being banned or not seen as good enough to be on video or something, or something like commercials).', 'time': 1670925111, 'resto': 134503003}, {'no': 134509518, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)05:01:50', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'A lot of old radio shows and early TV shows weren't recorded at all. The equipment they used could only perform live broadcasts.', 'time': 1670925710, 'resto': 134503003}]

name: Anonymous
com: What started the identity crisis many shows have had last decade over being episodic or serialized?
last_replies:
[{'no': 134508327, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)01:33:38', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>134508320
What do you mean?', 'filename': 'Bubbleline', 'ext': '.jpg', 'w': 1000, 'h': 1000, 'tn_w': 125, 'tn_h': 125, 'tim': 1670913218438021, 'time': 1670913218, 'md5': 'i4+0DiptAEcsO/SsuSCSqA==', 'fsize': 196989, 'resto': 134508320}, {'no': 134508667, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)02:18:42', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'kids need to grow up. kids will soon be not just the working class but also the government. it's very important to make them smart. not just get dopamine from slapstick humour and jokes every 5 seconds.', 'filename': 'thumb', 'ext': '.png', 'w': 1789, 'h': 1086, 'tn_w': 125, 'tn_h': 75, 'tim': 1670915922544929, 'time': 1670915922, 'md5': 'mw9LWVvBYD//CM55vVVQBQ==', 'fsize': 2978240, 'resto': 134508320}, {'no': 134508767, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)02:34:33', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>134508320
I think adventure time in spirit is very much like a random game of DnD. It can start out as just random one off adventures, but as you go along you start to build up more of a story to the world. That's what happened with adventure time, although the problem is that different people would come on board with different ideas on how things should happen and the story feels turbulent because of this, like a rollercoaster of quality. You have people like Rebecca Sugar who wanted Finn to have a love interest in FP, then when she left other people decided they were tired of that romance and broke them up for drama as an example.

Other shows that started out more episodic started to gain more continuity as time went on, but I don't think it was really natural like it was for AT. These shows seem like they wanted to be a serialised story from the beginning, taking inspiration from shows like Avatar the last airbender, or various anime. However the producers at the time were not interested in this, and were more interested in episodic comedies they could churn out and then air without having to worry about people missing parts of an overall story, as it's the best option from a money making perspective. So the common thing to do would be was creators Trojan Horse-ing the shows they wanted to create by disguising them as episodic comedies. That's why it feels these shows have an identify crisis, because they aren't really what they want to be from the start, and if they were they likely would struggle to find people to produce it.

An interesting sort of exception to this is Star Vs, and I say sort of as the original idea of Star Vs was in fact an episodic comedy about a young girl who just imagines she's a magical princess and there's a boy she's rivals with. But, was changed into being about an actual magical princess from another dimension.
